author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The International Criminal Court has warned atrocities committed in the Sudanese city of el-Fasher may amount to war crimes and crimes against humanity. 
There have been harrowing reports of mass killings, rapes and abductions, as the paramilitary Rapid Support Forces pushed the Sudanese Army out of the city last week.

The ICC said in a statement:
These atrocities are part of a broader pattern of violence that has afflicted the entire Darfur region since April 2023.
Such acts, if substantiated, may constitute war crimes and crimes against humanity under the Rome Statute.

The UN says the conflict in Sudan is the world's worst humanitarian crisis and the situation on the ground is rapidly deteriorating.
Aid agencies say around 200-thousand people remain trapped in el-Fasher in Sudan's Darfur region. 
They're living in desperate conditions and running out of food and water.
Tens of thousands of others, mostly women and children, have fled on foot to the nearby town of Tawila.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Turkish Foreign Minister Hakan Fidan says the country wants to do whatever is necessary for peace, “but we need to see an agreeable framework first”.

Fidan also said there are still major differences between the two parties that can’t be resolved in the short term, adding that Israel must stop its regular violations of the ceasefire and fulfil its duty to allow access to humanitarian aid.

The foreign minister added that countries will have to decide whether to send soldiers to the International Stabilisation Force – an international body whose establishment was part of Trump’s 20-point peace plan. The ISF is expected to guarantee security inside Gaza. Yet, there are still unanswered questions, including what kind of mandate the ISF would have, who would join and what would be its rules of engagement.

He was speaking after a ministerial meeting in Istanbul involving Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Jordan, Pakistan, Indonesia and Turkey.

The ceasefire in Gaza is again being tested, with Israel conducting several strikes on the strip on Monday morning.
Artillery shelling targeted Deir el-Balah in central Gaza. 
And in Khan Younis in the south, a Palestinian was injured after an Israeli drone strike. 
More than 230 Palestinians have been killed in Israeli attacks on the Strip since the agreement came into effect on October the 10th. 

In the last hour, Israel has released the bodies of several Palestinians.
They were transferred into Gaza through the Kissufim crossing.
It's part of the ceasefire agreement in which Hamas will hand over captives' bodies in exchange for Palestinian prisoners and bodies. 
This is the tenth such Israeli transfer.

It comes after Israel confirmed three bodies it received from Hamas overnight are those of Israeli captives.
The remains had been sent for forensic examination.
Israel confirmed all three captives had been army officials. 
Their families have been informed. 

Al Jazeera’s Tareq Abu

description:
The Trump administration must take action this week to restart the nation's largest anti-hunger program despite the government shutdown. That's according to a federal judge—who ordered emergency funds be tapped—after the food aid program that feeds 42 million Americans ran out of money on Saturday. But it's unclear how or when the emergency money will be disbursed—nor how long it will last.  

Al Jazeera's Heidi Zhou-Castro reports from Miami—one of the hardest-hit areas in the US.

description:
India’s southern megacity of #Bengaluru is one of the fastest growing cities in the world, driven by an IT boom and rapid urban expansion. 

But this growth has come at a cost. Snakes and other wildlife have lost most of their natural habitat and are increasingly forced to share spaces with humans.

Responsible for an estimated 58,000 deaths every year, snakes are feared as well as revered in India.

101 East meets Shuayb Ahmed, a snake rescuer on a mission.
